 of value and race occurred simultaneously. In so doing, she illustrates how racial capitalism denied the enslaved their kinship and affective ties while simultaneously relying on kinship to reproduce and enforce slavery through enslaved female bodies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aSlave tradexHistoryzAmerica. 0aSlave tradexHistoryzAtlantic Ocean Region. 0aSlave tradezAmericaxHistory. 0aSlave tradezAtlantic Ocean RegionxHistory. 0aSlaveryxEconomic aspectszAmerica. 0aSlaveryxPolitical aspectszAmerica. 0aWomen slaveszAmerica. 0aWomen slaveszAtlantic Ocean Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478021452zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021452/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles